In honor of National POW/MIA Recognition Day, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has issued a proclamation emphasizing the importance of remembering and honoring the sacrifices made by prisoners of war (POWs) and service members who remain missing in action (MIAs). The President acknowledges the pain and grief experienced by the families of the more than 81,600 missing service members who have yet to be accounted for. The iconic black and white POW/MIA flag is flown above the White House and in various locations across the country as a symbol of reverence and solidarity. The President reaffirms the commitment of the United States to recover and identify Americans missing from previous conflicts and expresses gratitude for the cooperation of partner nations in these efforts. The proclamation emphasizes that the United States will never abandon the search for missing service members and that they will never be forgotten. The President urges all Americans to observe National POW/MIA Recognition Day with appropriate ceremonies and activities.